# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: armin-laschet
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:armin-laschet/1949-west-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in West Germany on 14 August 1949 to elect the members of the first Bundestag, with a further eight seats elected in West Berlin between 1949 and January 1952 and another eleven between February 1952 and 1953.
[src:armin-laschet/1949-west-german-federal-election] They were the first free federal elections in West Germany since 1933 and the first after the division of the country.
[src:armin-laschet/1949-west-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU formed a centre-right coalition government with the FDP and the DP.
[src:armin-laschet/1949-west-german-federal-election] Most West German parties at the time of the 1949 Bundestag election were committed to democracy, but they disagreed on what kind of democracy West Germany should become.
[src:armin-laschet/1949-west-german-federal-election] The Christian Democratic (CDU) leader, 73-year-old Konrad Adenauer, former mayor of Cologne and party chairman in the British Zone since March 1946, believed in moderate, non-denominational and Christian democracy, social market economy and integration with the West.
[src:armin-laschet/1949-west-german-federal-election] In 1948 he had become president of the *Parlamentarischer Rat*, an office that added to his popularity as protagonist of a "state-to-be".
[src:armin-laschet/1949-west-german-federal-election] He attacked social democracy and the British, especially, dismantling of industry.
[src:armin-laschet/1949-west-german-federal-election] The Social Democratic (SPD) leader, Kurt Schumacher, wanted a united, democratic and socialist Germany.
[src:armin-laschet/1949-west-german-federal-election] He constantly accused Adenauer of betraying national interests, culminating in his heckling at the Bundestag session of 25 September 1949: "The Chancellor of the Allies!".
[src:armin-laschet/1949-west-german-federal-election] Schumacher criticized the Catholic Church, calling it the fifth occupying power and criticized denominational education.
[src:armin-laschet/1949-west-german-federal-election] In the end and to the great disappointment of the Social Democrats, the CDU/CSU outnumbered them by 31.0% to 29.2% of the votes cast.
[src:armin-laschet/1949-west-german-federal-election] To enter the Bundestag, a party had to surmount a threshold of 5% at least in one of the states or to win at least one electoral district; ten parties succeeded.
[src:armin-laschet/1949-west-german-federal-election] A number of non-voting members (elected in 1949:2 CDU, 5 SPD, 1 FDP; joined in February 1952 by: 3 CDU, 4 SPD, 4 FDP) indirectly elected by the West Berlin legislature (*Stadtverordnetenversammlung*) are included below in parentheses.
[src:armin-laschet/1949-west-german-federal-election] The French Saar Protectorate did not participate in this election.
[src:armin-laschet/1949-west-german-federal-election] 41 of the members elected to the Bundestag were refugees.
[src:armin-laschet/1949-west-german-federal-election] Schumacher had explicitly refused a grand coalition and led his party into opposition, where it would remain until December 1966, assuming the chair of the SPD parliamentary group as minority leader.
[src:armin-laschet/1949-west-german-federal-election] On 12 September 1949, he lost the indirect German presidential election, defeated by FDP chairman Theodor Heuss in the second ballot.
[src:armin-laschet/1949-west-german-federal-election] Schumacher died on 20 August 1952 of the long-term consequences of his concentration camp imprisonment during the Nazi years.
[src:armin-laschet/1949-west-german-federal-election] Adenauer had favoured the formation of a smaller centre-right coalition from the beginning.
[src:armin-laschet/1949-west-german-federal-election] Nominated by the CDU/CSU faction, he was elected the first Chancellor of the Federal Republic of Germany on 15 September 1949 by an absolute majority of 202 of 402 votes.
[src:armin-laschet/1949-west-german-federal-election] Adenauer had ensured that the votes of the predominantly Social Democrat West Berlin deputies did not count and later stated that he "naturally" had voted for himself.
[src:armin-laschet/1949-west-german-federal-election] On 20 September, he formed the Cabinet Adenauer I of CDU/CSU, FDP, and DP ministers.
[src:armin-laschet/1949-west-german-federal-election] Chosen as an interim Chancellor, he held the office until 1963, being re-elected three times (in 1953, in 1957 and in 1961).
[src:armin-laschet/1953-west-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in West Germany on 6 September 1953 to elect the members of the second Bundestag.
[src:armin-laschet/1953-west-german-federal-election] The Christian Democratic Union (CDU) emerged as the largest party.
[src:armin-laschet/1953-west-german-federal-election] This was the last election before Saarland joined West Germany in 1957.
[src:armin-laschet/1953-west-german-federal-election] It had been a separate entity, Saar protectorate, under French control since 1946.
[src:armin-laschet/1953-west-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU formed a center-right coalition government with the FDP, DP and GB/BHE, leaving the SPD as the main opposition.
[src:armin-laschet/1953-west-german-federal-election] In comparison to the 1949 election where ten parties won seats, only six parties won seats in the 1953 election, thus entailing a consolidation of the party system.
[src:armin-laschet/1953-west-german-federal-election] Federal Chancellor Konrad Adenauer (who was also CDU leader) campaigned on his policies of economic reconstruction and growth, moderate conservatism or Christian democracy, and close relations with the United States.
[src:armin-laschet/1953-west-german-federal-election] During the campaign he attacked the Social Democratic Party (SPD) ferociously.
[src:armin-laschet/1953-west-german-federal-election] His staff had a comfortable coach on a train previously used only by Hermann Göring and behind that a dining car with sleeping berths for journalists.
[src:armin-laschet/1953-west-german-federal-election] The new SPD leader (Kurt Schumacher had died in 1952) was Erich Ollenhauer, who was more moderate in his policies than Schumacher had been.
[src:armin-laschet/1953-west-german-federal-election] He did not oppose, in principle, the United States' military presence in Western Europe.
[src:armin-laschet/1953-west-german-federal-election] He later – in 1957 – supported a military alliance of most European countries, including Germany.
[src:armin-laschet/1953-west-german-federal-election] Konrad Adenauer remained Chancellor, governing in a broad coalition (two-thirds majority) with most of the minor parties except for the SPD and Centre Party.
[src:armin-laschet/1957-west-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in West Germany on 15 September 1957 to elect the members of the third Bundestag.
[src:armin-laschet/1957-west-german-federal-election] The Christian Democratic Union and its longtime ally, the Christian Social Union in Bavaria, won a sweeping victory, taking 270 seats in the Bundestag to win the first–and, to date, only–absolute majority for a single German parliamentary group in a free election.
[src:armin-laschet/1957-west-german-federal-election] This was the first West German federal election to take place in the Saarland, which–as Saar protectorate–had been a separate entity under French control between 1946 and 1956.
[src:armin-laschet/1957-west-german-federal-election] Only four parties won seats in the 1957 election, which was a consolidation of the party system relative to the 1953 and 1949 elections where six and ten parties won seats respectively.
[src:armin-laschet/1957-west-german-federal-election] As the CDU/CSU won a majority of seats, it formed a government without coalition partners.
[src:armin-laschet/1957-west-german-federal-election] West Germany had joined the European Economic Community in March 1957.
[src:armin-laschet/1957-west-german-federal-election] Its economy was growing steadily with very low unemployment, and most West Germans felt more prosperous and more secure than in 1949 or 1953.
[src:armin-laschet/1957-west-german-federal-election] Adenauer at first tried to brush the matter aside, but under heavy criticism from the press decided instead to meet with five of the physicists in Bonn.
[src:armin-laschet/1957-west-german-federal-election] Ultimately the row was too far away from the election itself to damage a surprisingly healthy looking Adenauer's prospects.
[src:armin-laschet/1957-west-german-federal-election] The All-German Bloc lost all of their seats, but the ideologically similar German Party maintained theirs.
[src:armin-laschet/1957-west-german-federal-election] The 1957 election was the last time that a right-wing populist party would return members to the Bundestag until Alternative for Germany's entrance in 2017.
[src:armin-laschet/1957-west-german-federal-election] The election also marked the last time until 1990 that any party other than CDU/CSU or SPD won any constituency seats.
[src:armin-laschet/1957-west-german-federal-election] Konrad Adenauer led the CDU-CSU coalition to a landslide victory.
[src:armin-laschet/1957-west-german-federal-election] The CDU-CSU won an outright majority— the only to date.
[src:armin-laschet/1957-west-german-federal-election] Since the CDU and the CSU form a single bloc in the Bundestag, this is the only time that a political party in Germany has been elected to a majority government in a free election.
[src:armin-laschet/1961-west-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in West Germany on 17 September 1961 to elect the members of the fourth Bundestag.
[src:armin-laschet/1961-west-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU remained the largest faction, winning 242 of the 499 seats.
[src:armin-laschet/1961-west-german-federal-election] The election campaign occurred in the context of the Berlin Crisis and the erection of the Berlin Wall.
[src:armin-laschet/1961-west-german-federal-election] For the first time, the SPD announced a Chancellor candidate who was not chairman of the party: Willy Brandt, the Governing Mayor of West Berlin.
[src:armin-laschet/1961-west-german-federal-election] After the building of the Berlin Wall, he gained more and more sympathy, while chancellor Konrad Adenauer was criticised for not showing enough support for the people of West Berlin.
[src:armin-laschet/1961-west-german-federal-election] Adenauer had to save the absolute majority of CDU and CSU, but, considering his age and his long term as chancellor, there were big doubts if he should lead the country in a fourth term.
[src:armin-laschet/1961-west-german-federal-election] The absolute majority was lost by the conservative union due to the gains of the liberal FDP under Erich Mende.
[src:armin-laschet/1961-west-german-federal-election] From 1961 on, the Union, SPD and FDP established an electoral "triopoly" in the Bundestag that would last until 1983.
[src:armin-laschet/1961-west-german-federal-election] Konrad Adenauer remained Chancellor, building a coalition between the CDU/CSU-FDP.
[src:armin-laschet/1961-west-german-federal-election] In 1962 he had to announce a fifth cabinet: The FDP had temporarily left the coalition after the secretary of defense, Franz Josef Strauß (CSU), had ordered the arrest of five journalists for publishing a memo detailing alleged weaknesses in the German armed forces (known as the Spiegel scandal).
[src:armin-laschet/1961-west-german-federal-election] In 1963 Adenauer finally retired; Ludwig Erhard took over his position as head of the coalition government.
[src:armin-laschet/1965-west-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in West Germany on 19 September 1965 to elect the members of the 5th Bundestag.
[src:armin-laschet/1965-west-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU remained the largest faction, while the Social Democratic Party remained the largest single party in the Bundestag, winning 217 of the 518 seats (including 15 of the 22 non-voting delegates for West Berlin).
[src:armin-laschet/1965-west-german-federal-election] Federal Chancellor Ludwig Erhard was initially popular as the acclaimed "father" of West Germany's economic miracle of the 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:armin-laschet/1965-west-german-federal-election] West Germany's economy still seemed solid in 1965, and thus not enough West German voters wanted to change the party of Federal Chancellor.
[src:armin-laschet/1965-west-german-federal-election] To ensure his victory in this Bundestag election, Erhard promised to cut income tax and to increase social program spending.
[src:armin-laschet/1965-west-german-federal-election] The coalition between the CDU/CSU and the FDP returned to government, with Ludwig Erhard as Chancellor.
[src:armin-laschet/1965-west-german-federal-election] In 1966, the FDP left the coalition over budget issues, and Erhard resigned.
[src:armin-laschet/1965-west-german-federal-election] Kurt Georg Kiesinger (also CDU) formed a new grand coalition between the CDU/CSU and the SPD which lasted until the next election.
[src:armin-laschet/1969-west-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in West Germany on 28 September 1969 to elect the members of the 6th Bundestag.
[src:armin-laschet/1969-west-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU remained the largest faction and the Social Democratic Party (SDP) remained the largest single party in the Bundestag, winning 237 of the 518 seats.
[src:armin-laschet/1969-west-german-federal-election] After the election, the SPD formed a coalition with the Free Democratic Party (FDP) and the former's leader Willy Brandt became the first Social Democratic Chancellor in West Germany's history, bringing an end to 20 years of CDU/CSU rule.
[src:armin-laschet/1969-west-german-federal-election] After the resignation of Chancellor Ludwig Erhard on 1 December 1966, a grand coalition of Christian Democrats and Social Democrats had governed West Germany under Chancellor Kurt Georg Kiesinger (CDU), with SPD chairman Willy Brandt as vice-chancellor and foreign minister.
[src:armin-laschet/1969-west-german-federal-election] Minister of Economic Affairs Karl Schiller (SPD) had proposed revaluing (increasing the external value of) the Deutsche Mark, West Germany's currency, to reduce the country's inflation rate and the rate of growth of the country's businesses' income.
[src:armin-laschet/1969-west-german-federal-election] He also sought to reduce West Germany's economic dependence on the exports.
[src:armin-laschet/1969-west-german-federal-election] However, Finance Minister Franz-Josef Strauss (CSU) rejected the Deutsche Mark's revaluation because Bavarian farmers, an important part of his constituency, opposed it.
[src:armin-laschet/1969-west-german-federal-election] The European Economic Community's food commodity prices were paid in U.S. dollars, and the Deutsche Mark's revaluation would have made West German exports less competitive (i.e. more expensive for other Western Europeans to buy).
[src:armin-laschet/1969-west-german-federal-election] The coalition had already effectively ended before the election because of the revaluation dispute.
[src:armin-laschet/1969-west-german-federal-election] In addition, enough West German voters were willing to give the Social Democratic leader, Foreign Minister Willy Brandt, a chance to govern West Germany.
[src:armin-laschet/1969-west-german-federal-election] Brandt, who ran for the third time after 1961 and 1965, had shown sympathy towards groups, including left-wing intellectuals and activists of the German student movement, who had felt ignored by the Christian Democrat-led coalition governments.
[src:armin-laschet/1969-west-german-federal-election] In addition, his intellect, self-control and reputation for honesty appealed to ordinary West Germans.
[src:armin-laschet/1969-west-german-federal-election] Willy Brandt, against the will of several party fellows like Herbert Wehner or Helmut Schmidt, chose to leave the grand coalition with the CDU/CSU, forming a social-liberal coalition with the Free Democratic Party (FDP) instead.
[src:armin-laschet/1969-west-german-federal-election] On 21 October 1969 he was elected Chancellor of Germany, the first SPD chancellor in the postwar period, after the last Social Democrat holding this position had been Hermann Müller from 1928 to 1930.
[src:armin-laschet/1969-west-german-federal-election] FDP chairman Walter Scheel succeeded Brandt as vice-chancellor and foreign minister.
[src:armin-laschet/1969-west-german-federal-election] Brandt's government proceeded with the revaluation Schiller had proposed, raising the value of the mark by 9.3% in late October.
[src:armin-laschet/1969-west-german-federal-election] Disappointed Kiesinger bitterly complained about the faithless liberals.
[src:armin-laschet/1969-west-german-federal-election] Though he had again achieved the plurality of votes for the CDU, he had to lead his party into opposition.
[src:armin-laschet/1969-west-german-federal-election] He was succeeded as chairman by Rainer Barzel in 1971.
[src:armin-laschet/1969-west-german-federal-election] However the Cabinet Brandt I could only rely on an absolute majority (*Kanzlermehrheit*) of twelve votes in the Bundestag.
[src:armin-laschet/1969-west-german-federal-election] Several party switches in protest against Brandt's *Ostpolitik* of FDP and SPD members resulted in the snap election of 1972.
[src:armin-laschet/1972-west-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in West Germany on 19 November 1972 to elect the members of the seventh Bundestag.
[src:armin-laschet/1972-west-german-federal-election] In the first snap elections since the resumption of democratic elections in 1949, the Social Democratic Party (SPD) emerged as the largest party in parliament, winning 230 of the 496 seats.
[src:armin-laschet/1972-west-german-federal-election] The SPD's Willy Brandt remained chancellor after resuming his coalition government with the Free Democratic Party.
[src:armin-laschet/1972-west-german-federal-election] On 27 April 1972 the opposition had tried to have CDU leader Rainer Barzel elected new chancellor in a constructive vote of no confidence, but Barzel surprisingly missed the majority of 249 by two votes.
[src:armin-laschet/1972-west-german-federal-election] Rumours that at least one member of the CDU/CSU faction had been paid by the East German *Stasi* to abstain (in effect, voting against Barzel) were confirmed by Markus Wolf, former head of the *Hauptverwaltung Aufklärung*, in 1997.
[src:armin-laschet/1972-west-german-federal-election] Nevertheless, the following budget debates revealed that the government's majority was lost and only the upcoming organisation of the 1972 Summer Olympics in Munich delayed the arrangement of new elections.
[src:armin-laschet/1972-west-german-federal-election] On 22 September 1972 Chancellor Brandt asked for a vote of confidence, which required the same majority of 249 "yes" votes: it failed with 233 "yes" votes to 246 "no" votes.
[src:armin-laschet/1972-west-german-federal-election] The members of the government did not participate (in effect, voting no) to ensure the vote would fail, however it would have regardless.
[src:armin-laschet/1972-west-german-federal-election] This allowed Brandt to advise President Gustav Heinemann to dissolve the Bundestag and call new elections the same day.
[src:armin-laschet/1972-west-german-federal-election] In the tense campaign, the CDU/CSU attacked Brandt as being too lenient towards Eastern Europe and having the wrong ideas on the economy.
[src:armin-laschet/1972-west-german-federal-election] SPD and FDP benefited from the enormous personal popularity of the chancellor, laureate of the 1971 Nobel Peace Prize.
[src:armin-laschet/1972-west-german-federal-election] He gained the support by numerous celebrities of the West German culture and media scene (e.g.
[src:armin-laschet/1972-west-german-federal-election] Günter Grass), expressed by the slogan *Willy wählen!* ("Vote for Willy!").
[src:armin-laschet/1972-west-german-federal-election] Voter turnout was 91.1%, the highest ever since 1949.
[src:armin-laschet/1972-west-german-federal-election] In 1970 the voting age had been lowered from 21 to 18.
[src:armin-laschet/1972-west-german-federal-election] The SPD celebrated their best result ever, representing the largest faction in the German parliament for the first time since the 1930 Reichstag elections.
[src:armin-laschet/1972-west-german-federal-election] It enabled the party to nominate Annemarie Renger for President of the Bundestag; she was the first Social Democrat and also the first woman to hold this office.
[src:armin-laschet/1972-west-german-federal-election] On 14 December 1972 the Bundestag MPs of the social-liberal coalition re-elected Willy Brandt chancellor.
[src:armin-laschet/1972-west-german-federal-election] His Cabinet Brandt II returned to government the next day, again with FDP chairman Walter Scheel as vice-chancellor and foreign minister.
[src:armin-laschet/1972-west-german-federal-election] Defeated Rainer Barzel resigned as CDU chairman on 9 May 1973; he was succeeded by Helmut Kohl.
[src:armin-laschet/1972-west-german-federal-election] On 7 May 1974, Brandt would resign in the course of the Guillaume Affair, after one of his personal aides had been unmasked as a *Stasi* agent.
[src:armin-laschet/1972-west-german-federal-election] The coalition continued under his party fellow Helmut Schmidt, while Brandt remained SPD chairman until 1987.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Laschet earned a law degree and worked as a journalist before and during his early political career.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] In 1994 he was elected to the Bundestag and in 1999 he became a Member of the European Parliament.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] In 2005 he entered state politics in North Rhine-Westphalia as a member of the state government.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] In 2012 he became leader of the state party, and he was elected Prime Minister of the state in 2017.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] His Cabinet consisted of members of his own CDU and the liberal Free Democratic Party (FDP).
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] In January 2021, Laschet was elected leader of the CDU, winning 52.8% of delegates votes against Friedrich Merz in the second round of the contest.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] The result of the election was certified by postal vote of the party conference's delegates with the final result announced on 22 January.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] It was confirmed on 20 April 2021 that he would be the CDU/CSU candidate for Chancellor of Germany at the 2021 German federal election, after rival Markus Söder conceded.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] He was born to an observant Roman Catholic family of German-speaking Walloon origin; his father's parents were both of Belgian origin.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] He is married to Susanne Malangré, whom he met in a Catholic children's choir when they were children and who is a member of a prominent Aachen political family of French-speaking Walloon origin.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] On 9 February 2024, he was awarded an honorary doctorate from TED University.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Laschet is a lecturer for political science at LMU Munich.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Laschet was born in Burtscheid, a suburb of Aachen, about three kilometres from the Belgian and Dutch borders, to parents Heinrich Laschet and Marcella née Frings; he was raised in an observant Roman Catholic family.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] His father was a mining engineer at a black coal mine and later became an elementary school teacher and headmaster.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Like many others in the tri-border area the Laschets had relatives across the national boundaries, who lived in Belgium, The Netherlands, Germany and Neutral Moresnet.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Laschet maintains close personal ties to Belgium where members of the Laschet family still live.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] He attended the Pius-Gymnasium in Aachen and studied law at the University of Bonn and LMU Munich, passing the first state examination in law in 1987.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] He studied journalism from 1986 to 1988.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] In Munich, he became a member of K.D.St.V.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Aenania München, a Catholic student fraternity that is member of the Cartellverband.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Laschet worked as a journalist and in the publishing industry from 1986 until 1991, among other things as Bonn correspondent for Bayerischer Rundfunk.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] He later served as editor-in-chief of the Catholic newspaper *KirchenZeitung Aachen* from 1991 until 1994.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] From 1995 to 1999, while also serving as a member of parliament, he was CEO of the Catholic publishing company Einhard-Verlag, which had previously been led by his father-in-law Heinrich Malangré.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] After serving as staffer to the President of the Bundestag, Laschet became a member of the German Bundestag in the 1994 election.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] He was elected in the single-member constituency of Aachen I, after the incumbent Hans Stercken retired.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] He was on the Committee for Economic Cooperation and Development and on the Committee for European Union Affairs.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] In addition, he was part of the so-called "Pizza-Connection" (a reference to an American drug ring).
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] A number of informal meeting of a group of young Bundestag Members from both the CDU and the Greens.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] This was later seen as controversial, because it solidified an image of him as a liberal/centrist member of the CDU.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] He lost re-election in the 1998 SPD landslide to future Health Minister Ulla Schmidt.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] As Member of the European Parliament, Laschet served on the Committee on Budgets between 1999 and 2001 and on the Committee on Foreign Affairs between 2002 and 2005.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] In the latter capacity, he served as the Parliament's rapporteur on relations between the EU and the United Nations.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Under Minister President Jürgen Rüttgers in North Rhine-Westphalia, Laschet served as State Minister for Generations, Family, Women and Integration from 2005 until 2010, and as State Minister for Federal Affairs, Europe and Media from 2010.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] In 2010, he unsuccessfully ran against Norbert Röttgen for the post of CDU chairman in the state.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] When Röttgen resigned from that office in 2012, Laschet was elected as his successor.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] On 4 December 2012, he was elected as one of five deputy chairpersons of the national CDU party, serving alongside Volker Bouffier, Julia Klöckner, Thomas Strobl and Ursula von der Leyen.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Laschet currently serves as state MP in the Landtag of North Rhine-Westphalia and also chairs the CDU's state chapter (Landesverband).
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] From 2014 until 2016, he was a member of the North Rhine-Westphalia Commission for Constitutional Reform, led by Rainer Bovermann.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] In November 2015, Laschet visited the Zaatari refugee camp in Jordan to learn more about the plight of Syrians fleeing the violence in the ongoing Syrian civil war that erupted in 2011.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Between March 2015 and January 2016, he chaired the Robert Bosch Expert Commission to Consider a Realignment of Refugee Policy, an expert group convened by the Robert Bosch Stiftung.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] In November 2016, Laschet was elected leading candidate for the North Rhine-Westphalia state elections in May 2017 which he won in what was widely considered an upset victory.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] He was a CDU delegate to the Federal Convention for the purpose of electing the President of Germany in 2017.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] In December 2016, Laschet presided over the CDU's national convention in Essen.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Laschet served as the 11th Minister President of North Rhine-Westphalia from 2017 to 2021.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Laschet's government was a coalition between the Christian Democratic Union (CDU) and the Free Democratic Party (FDP).
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] As one of his state's representatives at the Bundesrat, he serves as a member of the Federal Committee on Foreign Affairs and the Defence Committee.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] He named Jens Spahn as his vice-presidential candidate, with Friedrich Merz and Norbert Röttgen as his challengers.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Polls subsequently showed that voters rated Laschet's management of the COVID-19 pandemic in Germany's most populous state poorly.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] The election of the new CDU party president, after several postponements due to the coronavirus epidemic, took place only at the two-day party congress in mid-January 2021, which was the first fully digital congress in the party's history.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] On the second day of the congress, 16 January 2021, Laschet won 38.42% of the votes in the first round and 52.79% in the second round.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] He thus became the new president of the CDU.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] After his defeat at the head of his party in the federal elections, he resigned from the party leadership on 7 October.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] His place was taken by Merz, who finally succeeded in his third attempt, in the election of the party president on 17 December 2021.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] However, the strong intra-party divisions that were also evident in the vote could have led to a joint CDU/CSU chancellorship candidacy for Markus Söder, the president of the smaller Bavarian sister party, the CSU.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Polls conducted immediately before the party congress showed that 55 percent of voters considered Söder a good candidate for chancellor, while 80 percent of CDU/CSU supporters thought he was a good candidate, compared to only 27 percent and 32 percent respectively for Laschet.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Subsequently, following a late-night meeting of the CDU leadership in Berlin, it was announced that in a secret ballot, 77.5 percent of those present at the meeting had finally backed Laschet, compared to just 22.5 percent for Söder.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Thus, it was a foregone conclusion that Armin Laschet would be in the running to become chancellor of the CDU/CSU coalition in September 2021.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Already at the party congress in Rhineland-Palatinate in May 2021, Laschet called for the Greens to be the main political opponent in the upcoming election campaign.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] He set the goal of preventing the formation of a Red–Red–Green (SPD–Left–Greens) coalition.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] As his party's candidate to succeed Merkel in the national elections, Laschet was initially seen as having made an uncertain start to his campaign and faced calls to chart a more right-wing course to win back voters disenchanted by the incumbent coalition government.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] However, the party's win in the Saxony-Anhalt elections was later interpreted as a boost to Laschet.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Laschet presented the joint CDU/CSU election platform with Söder on 21 June 2021.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] In the programme, they stated that combating the pandemic, climate change and defending prosperity and freedom are global challenges, and that their goal is to create a Germany open to the world, which strives for both modernisation and green policies.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] While visiting Erftstadt, a flood-hit town, Laschet was caught laughing on camera and came under fire later despite his apology that 'It was stupid and shouldn't have happened and I regret it'.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] This was a decisive factor in the fact that all but 7 percent of those surveyed were positive about the provincial premier's management of the flood crisis.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Following this incident, CDU/CSU suffered heavily in opinion polls and SPD took the lead.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Laschet faced another scandal at the end of the month, when it emerged that he, like his fellow Green Party candidate for chancellor Annalena Baerbock, was facing accusations of plagiarism.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Zuwanderung als Chance*, was written in 2009 and he finally admitted his "mistake", and apologised.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] In the 2021 German federal election on 26 September, Laschet had to compete for the post of Chancellor against Olaf Scholz of the SPD.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] He did not contest an individual constituency.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] His home constituency of Aachen I, which he had represented from 1994 to 1998 and was expected to be his constituency, swung to the Greens on election day.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Opinion poll predictions came true, with the SPD winning the most votes (25.7%), while the CDU/CSU had their worst result ever (24.1%).
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] His former constituency of Aachen I, which he had represented from 1994 to 1998, swung to the Greens on election day.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Alliance 90/The Greens finished third with 14.8%, just ahead of the FDP with 11.5%, and both became the "kingmakers".
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Two months later, they came together with the SDP to form a coalition and Olaf Scholz was elected chancellor.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Following the election, Laschet claimed personal responsibility for the party's loss.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] After the election, Laschet resigned as Minister President of North Rhine-Westphalia on 25 October 2021 in order to resume his membership of the Bundestag.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] He also resigned as the Leader of the CDU and was replaced by Friedrich Merz, who had won the leadership contest.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] He remained a member of the Bundestag after being re-elected on the North Rhine-Westphalia party list and sat on multiple subcommittees.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] He was nominated as the CDU's candidate for his former constituency of Aachen I in the 2025 German federal election.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Since 2025, Laschet has been serving as chairman of the German Parliament's Committee on Foreign Affairs.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Laschet has been criticised for hesitancy in efforts to mitigate climate change.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] As Minister President of North Rhine-Westphalia he claimed that the state was a "pioneer" in climate protection.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Environmental organisations have rebuked this claim.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] During his tenure, the expansion of wind power collapsed in North Rhine-Westphalia, so that only a third of the originally planned turbines were built.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] His state government also allowed the phaseout of three coal-fired power plants to last until 2038.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] In 2018, shortly after taking over as Minister President of North Rhine-Westphalia, Laschet supported the minister of the environment Christina Schulze Föcking's decision to dismantle the state's administrative department for environmental crimes.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Public broadcaster WDR reported that prior to its dismantling the department had been investigating accusations over pig farming at the farm of Schulze Föcking's family.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] On European integration, Laschet seeks to strengthen the European Union on issues such as fighting international terrorism and organized crime, as well as energy policy.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] He also wants to see the President of the European Commission be elected directly by EU voters.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] During the European debt crisis, Laschet called for an "open discussion" toward a broad solution to the debt crisis, of which Eurobonds could be a part.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] He argued that a Greek exit from the Eurozone could trigger undesirable upheaval in southern Europe: "(An exit) could lead to instability in a NATO member state.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Russia is standing ready with billions to help Greece in such a scenario." In October 2011, he signed George Soros' open letter calling for more European Union involvement in the single currency turmoil.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] In 2020 alone, Laschet met with French president Emmanuel Macron three times.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Alongside Jens Spahn, Laschet was invited by Macron of France to attend the 2020 Bastille Day celebrations in Paris, in a sign of gratitude for their role in helping French citizens during the COVID-19 pandemic in France.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] In an honour reserved for special guests, Macron invited Laschet into the Élysée Palace's gardens.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Laschet was a fierce defender of Chancellor Merkel's migration policies during the European migrant crisis of 2015.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] In 2016, Laschet dismissed proposals for a so-called burqa ban as a "phony debate" and distraction from more pressing issues.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] However, his party later adopted this policy as a core issue.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Ahead of a parliamentary vote in June 2017, Laschet expressed his opposition against Germany's introduction of same-sex marriage, going so far as to say it would be unconstitutional.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] During the 2021 German federal election Laschet gave a different position in a town hall, where he claimed he would have voted in favour of same-sex marriage.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] In 2018, Laschet described the treehouses protesting the destruction of Hambach forest as "illegally occupied areas" and stated that RWE had the right to clear the forest.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] "The state government is there to ensure that the law that applies is enforced," he said during a talk show on German public broadcaster *WDR*.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Laschet considers Germany to be insufficiently prepared for global political challenges.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] In his view, the country lacks the will to pursue a foreign policy that is independent of other major powers such as Russia or the US.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] In 2015, Laschet was criticised for not standing up for German interests when it was revealed that US intelligence agencies are illegally spying on German citizens and businesses.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] German experts estimate that by the year 2000, American industrial espionage was already causing annual economic losses of at least €10 billion per year due to stolen inventions and development projects – the number having likely only risen since then due to the increase of digitisation.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Despite these revelations, Laschet supported Angela Merkel's policy, which in leaked cables was revealed to be to "sit out" the pressure from the German public and Bundestag.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Laschet is considered by some critics as taking a soft stance on the government of President Vladimir Putin.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Laschet has voiced support for Nord Stream 2 and for a closer relationship with China and is against excluding Huawei from Germany's 5G network.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] However, Germany's Federal Office for Information Security has supported Laschet's position, saying that comprehensive investigations into Huawei's hardware and software have produced no evidence of wrongdoing and that an exclusion is unjustified.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Barkin further argues that Laschet has also been against "demonizing" Putin for the Russian annexation of Crimea.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] At the same time, Laschet said that Germany should increase military spending and take on a greater share of military burdens within NATO.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] He argued that the Bundeswehr should take on more responsibility in Africa, around the Mediterranean and in Mali.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] In 2018, Laschet cancelled his appearances at the Ruhrtriennale arts and music festival due to the festival allowing supporters of the BDS movement to perform.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] In 2013, Laschet criticised Foreign Minister Guido Westerwelle's support for rebels in the civil war in Syria: "It is absurd that the same people we are fighting in Mali are being supported in Syria.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] It is the terrorist groups al-Nusra and al-Qaida, financed from Qatar and Saudi Arabia, who are introducing Sharia courts and fighting Syria's religious diversity".
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] In 2013, Laschet also criticised Westerwelle's demand to release former President Mohammed Mursi after the coup in Egypt in 2013, as minorities and Christians in particular had suffered under Mursi.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Laschet described the chaotic withdrawal of Western troops from Afghanistan and Fall of Kabul to the Taliban in August 2021 as the "biggest debacle that NATO has suffered since its founding".
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] In November 2023, Laschet criticised the German federal government for not voting against United Nations General Assembly Resolution ES-10/21.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] Laschet is married to his childhood sweetheart Susanne Malangré, whom he met as a child in a Catholic children's choir led by Susanne's father, prominent business executive Heinrich Malangré; they married in 1985.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] The family resides in Aachen's Burtscheid district.
[src:armin-laschet/armin-laschet] His son Johannes ("Joe") Laschet, who studies law, is a blogger and model, described as a fashion influencer on Instagram.
